			<ns0:name>b...@google.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/105821748722532785568/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">the NaClMutex object in the platform library implements a host-OS independent abstraction of mutex objects.  unfortunately, there is an observable platform difference that has heretofore been unnoticed: on windows, the mutexes that it implements are recursive (which is the default on windows for both event-based locks and critical section-based locks), whereas on other POSIX pthread-based systems the mutexes are binary.

a test is forthcoming.  what is somewhat surprising is that this platform difference is exposed not only by the newlib-based toolchain, but also by the glibc-based one.  i'm unclear how the futex emulation code is making this attribute exposed, but i haven't delved into that code.</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2012-05-23T20:35:54.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2012-05-17T11:29:52.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:status>Fixed</ns2:status><ns2:owner>
